TRICHOMONIASIS, AVIAN - CANADA (02): (NEWFOUNDLAND AND LABRADOR)
****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 14 Oct 2016 2:50 PM NT
Source: CBC (Canadian Broadcasting Corporation) News [edited]
http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/newfoundland-labrador/juncos-pub-closing-bird-disease-1.3804943


Junco's Pub, an elaborately designed bird feeder described by its creator as a "miniature bar for wild birds", has announced it is closing down. On Facebook, the pub's owner and operator, Elling Lien, explained why he's closing its doors. "It's with a heavy heart that I let you know that I've decided to close Junco's Pub. While it hasn't appeared at the pub, the recent frounce [trichomoniasis] scare on the east coast of Newfoundland has taken the fun out of feeding wild birds."

Possible signs of a parasitic infection known as frounce are being spotted in Newfoundland and Labrador birds, and that has the province's top veterinarian asking the public to take precautions. Frounce attacks the bird's crop, a pouch in its throat that's part of its digestive system. It can be fatal to birds but does not affect humans. "It causes an infection in the crop of the bird that makes them be unable to swallow, essentially, and they can't eat and they sort of waste away," said chief veterinary officer Dr Laura Rogers, adding the parasite also causes inflammation and ulcers.

Lien is asking other people in the province with bird feeders to consider removing theirs too. "I encourage other folks to listen to the advice of the experts like Laura Rogers and take their feeders down -- at the very least until winter each year. And even in winter, try to only use feeders as an emergency support during cold snaps or bad weather," he said.

[byline: Mark Quinn]

