[_Trichomonas gallinae_ is a common protozoan parasite of pigeons (Columbiformes), which principally infects the upper alimentary tract where it can cause necrotic ingluvitis (inflammation of the crop and esophagus). Epidemic mortality in columbiform species has been previously reported, and the parasite may infect other avian taxa such as birds of prey and songbirds. Trichomoniasis has been postulated to be a factor contributing to the extinction of the passenger pigeon _Ectopistes migratorius_ and has been shown to be a significant cause of nestling mortality in the Mauritius Island-endemic pink pigeon _Nesoenas mayeri_ and in the Iberian Peninsula population of the Bonelli's eagle _Hieraaetus fasciatus_.

Although it had been assumed that the parasite caused little pathogenic effect on non-columbiformes, recent studies showed trichomonads were associated with morbidity and mortality amongst free ranging house finches, mockingbirds, and corvids.

Feeders can enhance the transmission of this parasite, and also of other diseases such as mycoplasmosis and salmonellosis. - Mod.PMB

Maps of Canada can be seen at http://www.map-of-canada.org/canada-map-795.jpg and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4563228,375. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
